In the introduction to this paper, I quoted Avtar Brah for stating that what matters is not just who travels, but also the circumstances under which the travelling takes place. It should be emphasized that the question of ‘circumstances’ is a discursive as well as a material one. What matters is not just ‘who can travel where, when and how?’ but also ‘who gets to tell the story?’ Clifford illustrates the significance of who is doing the accounting of the travel as travel by pointing to the difference between interpretations of the activities of Victorian bourgeois travellers on the one hand and the activities of their accompanying – often non<span style="font-family: 'Cambria Math',serif;">‐</span>white – servants on the other. The servants never acquired the status of ‘travellers’ because, ‘in the dominant discourses of travel, a non<span style="font-family: 'Cambria Math',serif;">‐</span>white person cannot figure as a heroic explorer, aesthetic interpreter, or scientific authority’ (Clifford, 1997, p. 33).4 Here, an important criterion for being a ‘true traveller’ is closely related to (racially defined) criteria for who can be perceived as an interpreting subject.5¶ The conventions determining who can meaningfully be described as a ‘traveller’, and thus as an active subject and interpreter of the world, have of course changed since Victorian travellers set out with their staff of servants. The inclination to set up hierarchies between more or less ‘authentic’ travellers has not changed, however. Hierarchical distinctions between movements are not only encountered when travellers of various kinds attempt to distinguish themselves in relation to mass tourism (cf. Urry, 1990; Kaplan, 1996) or even avoid the ‘tourist’ label altogether, as when organizers as well as participants in heritage tours prefer to interpret their travel in terms of a ‘pilgrimage’.6 We also meet it in Ulf Hannerz' distinction between the cosmopolitan attitude on the one hand and what he calls